1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
Welcome to this new in-depth analysis.

2
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:08,080
Okay, let's get straight to the point and tackle one of the most fascinating mysteries of politics

3
00:00:08,080 --> 00:00:09,580
and modern economics.

4
00:00:09,580 --> 00:00:14,599
Do United States presidents lie about taxes? In short, does their rhetoric and the big

5
00:00:14,599 --> 00:00:19,140
promises we hear in speeches actually align with the reality of tax

6
00:00:19,140 --> 00:00:22,679
reforms? It is an absolutely crucial question.

7
00:00:22,679 --> 00:00:26,320
We often tend to dismiss political speeches, don't we?

8
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:31,240
We consider them simple background noise, but a very rigorous economic study, recently

9
00:00:31,240 --> 00:00:36,480
published in the American Economic Journal, shows us that there is much, much more beneath

10
00:00:36,480 --> 00:00:37,480
the surface.

11
00:00:37,480 --> 00:00:41,480
And as we will see, the answer to this question will lead us to discover some

12
00:00:41,480 --> 00:00:43,679
literally unexpected dynamics.

13
00:00:43,679 --> 00:00:47,359
Let's move to the first section: the mystery of promises.

14
00:00:47,359 --> 00:00:50,200
Do presidents' words become reality?

15
00:00:50,200 --> 00:00:55,079
Historically, measuring whether a politician is telling the truth and what the real economic impact

16
00:00:55,079 --> 00:00:58,719
of their words is, well, has always been quite a puzzle.

17
00:00:58,719 --> 00:01:03,039
Leaders often make vague promises months or even years before writing an actual

18
00:01:03,039 --> 00:01:08,640
law, while markets and citizens listen and react in the meantime.

19
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:09,959
Let's take a concrete example.

20
00:01:09,959 --> 00:01:15,840
January 1981, President Ronald Reagan declared: "It's time to awaken this industrial

21
00:01:15,840 --> 00:01:19,799
giant and to lighten our punitive tax burden."

22
00:01:19,799 --> 00:01:24,560
Boom—months before the actual reform, with these exact words, he sent an

23
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:25,560
unmistakable signal.

24
00:01:25,560 --> 00:01:29,359
There isn't even half a line of law written in Parliament yet, and yet the message arrives

25
00:01:29,359 --> 00:01:30,359
loud and clear.

26
00:01:30,359 --> 00:01:35,879
The question then is, can we measure these signals systematically to see if they truly

27
00:01:35,879 --> 00:01:36,879
turn into reality?

28
00:01:36,879 --> 00:01:39,719
And this brings us to section 2.

29
00:01:39,719 --> 00:01:44,400
60 years of presidential speeches: a massive data archive.

30
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:50,680
To solve this true enigma, researchers didn't rely on opinions

31
00:01:50,680 --> 00:01:52,560
or a few isolated anecdotes.

32
00:01:52,560 --> 00:01:54,400
They did things in a big way.

33
00:01:54,400 --> 00:1:59,719
They took the entire—literally the entire—archive of public presidential

34
00:01:59,719 --> 00:02:03,159
speeches from the post-war era to today.

35
00:02:03,159 --> 00:02:09,879
The numbers are crazy; we're talking about exactly 1,119,200 paragraphs, extracted

36
00:02:09,879 --> 00:02:15,360
from nearly 60,000 presidential texts between 1949 and 2017.

37
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:20,360
It's a mountain of data; no human being, not even the fastest team of scholars in the

38
00:02:20,360 --> 00:02:25,200
world, could ever objectively read and analyze all of this to find

39
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:29,120
recurring patterns; a different approach was definitely needed.

40
00:02:29,120 --> 00:02:35,520
So we come to section 3: the algorithm reads politics, artificial intelligence

41
00:02:35,520 --> 00:02:37,320
analyzes the texts.

42
00:02:37,320 --> 00:02:42,480
Since human reading was physically impossible, researchers relied on an

43
00:02:42,480 --> 00:02:48,880
advanced algorithm called Latent Dirichlet Allocation—no need to panic over the complicated name—they used it

44
00:02:48,879 --> 00:02:53,639
to isolate in a completely neutral way the sentences that specifically discussed tax

45
00:02:53,639 --> 00:02:54,639
reforms.

46
00:02:54,639 --> 00:02:59,680
To be clear, we're talking about topic modeling; just imagine it as a massive

47
00:02:59,680 --> 00:03:05,439
automated sorting system, a super-intelligent machine that reads millions of words, and looking only

48
00:03:05,439 --> 00:03:10,280
at the context and the frequency with which these words appear together, starts tossing them into different virtual

49
00:03:10,280 --> 00:03:11,280
baskets.

50
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:16,719
If it notices that "war," "troops," "defense" always appear together, it creates the "military" basket.

51
00:03:16,719 --> 00:03:21,680
Well, they had the machine do exactly the same thing to discover how presidents

52
00:03:21,680 --> 00:03:22,680
talk about taxes.

53
00:03:22,680 --> 00:03:28,599
And look at the results: observing the keywords extracted by the algorithm for the topic

54
00:03:28,599 --> 00:03:33,319
"tax increase," you can see clearly how the system hit the bullseye.

55
00:03:33,319 --> 00:03:39,800
The words written in large print, such as "deficit," "budget," and very obviously "social security,"

56
00:03:39,800 --> 00:03:43,879
are exactly the ones that appear most often when the political groundwork is being laid

57
00:03:43,879 --> 00:03:45,280
to raise taxes.

58
00:03:45,800 --> 00:03:50,199
And here's the best part, because the comparison is truly illuminating.

59
00:03:50,199 --> 00:03:54,199
The algorithm learned to distinguish the vocabulary of politicians.

60
00:03:54,199 --> 00:03:59,840
When tax increases are in the air, the words revolve around social security, deficit,

61
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:05,039
budget; but watch out, when a president—and it absolutely doesn't matter which political party

62
00:04:05,039 --> 00:04:10,960
they belong to—wants to signal a tax cut, well, the words change completely,

63
00:04:10,960 --> 00:04:16,079
terms like Small Business, Growth, or Job Creation pop up; it's a

64
00:04:16,079 --> 00:04:22,120
systemic division of language, it works for everyone, across all administrations.

65
00:04:22,120 --> 00:04:27,960
Let's go to section 4: predicting tax reforms, the verdict of the data.

66
00:04:27,960 --> 00:04:30,519
So, what is the final verdict?

67
00:04:30,519 --> 00:04:33,759
Very simple: the algorithm works perfectly.

68
00:04:33,759 --> 00:04:38,680
The crazy discovery is that the frequency of these specific topics in speeches

69
00:04:38,680 --> 00:04:41,759
truly manages to predict future tax laws.

70
00:04:41,759 --> 00:04:46,759
The data shows that these speeches have what economists call Granger

71
00:04:46,759 --> 00:04:49,400
causality with respect to actual reforms.

72
00:04:49,400 --> 00:04:52,960
In simple terms, they are a highly reliable statistical indicator.

73
00:04:52,960 --> 00:04:58,000
They anticipate the direction—whether taxes will go up or down—and predict real changes

74
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:02,000
in the state coffers and what is, perhaps even more incredible,

75
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,720
they influence investor expectations, driving financial markets and interest rates,

76
00:05:06,760 --> 00:05:09,760
long before the laws are actually voted on.

77
00:05:09,760 --> 00:05:15,720
This confirms a crucial fact, analyzing all administrations in recent history,

78
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:20,840
from Nixon to Obama, without any distinction between conservatives or progressives.

79
00:05:20,840 --> 00:05:27,480
Political rhetoric is a surprisingly accurate indicator of the true tax policy to come.

80
00:05:27,480 --> 00:05:32,680
In practice, a president's words are the very first piece of information that begins to shape

81
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:36,000
the economic behavior of the entire nation.

82
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:43,000
And here we enter section 5: the waiting paradox, an economic plot twist.

83
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:49,720
Okay, we've understood that the signals are there and are super precise, but what happens to the economy

84
00:05:49,720 --> 00:05:53,480
when these signals arrive, perhaps, well in advance?

85
00:05:53,480 --> 00:05:57,920
Here we must absolutely explore an absurd and decidedly

86
00:05:57,920 --> 00:06:00,560
paradoxical side effect of transparency in politics.

87
00:06:00,560 --> 00:06:05,360
The fundamental question to understand this counter-intuitive reality is: what happens when the

88
00:06:05,360 --> 00:06:09,080
market knows far in advance that a big tax cut is coming?

89
00:06:09,080 --> 00:06:13,879
Logic would lead us to think, well, great news—businesses and citizens will have more

90
00:06:13,879 --> 00:06:17,080
money in their pockets, there will be an immediate economic boom.

91
00:06:17,080 --> 00:06:18,080
Right?

92
00:06:18,080 --> 00:06:19,080
Wrong.

93
00:06:19,080 --> 00:06:21,920
Economic reality shows us a completely flipped picture.

94
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:26,520
Macroeconomic data gives us an answer that will leave you speechless.

95
00:06:26,520 --> 00:06:31,520
Looking at the sudden drop traced on this graph, you notice something incredible.

96
00:06:31,519 --> 00:06:36,759
When a future tax cut is announced, the economy initially contracts.

97
00:06:36,759 --> 00:06:40,959
There is a real drop in GDP, even before the cut becomes a reality.

98
00:06:40,959 --> 00:06:44,560
The curve literally drops below zero in the first few quarters.

99
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:47,159
It's a completely counter-intuitive result.

100
00:06:47,159 --> 00:06:48,519
Crazy, right?

101
00:06:48,519 --> 00:06:52,680
Let's try to summarize the reason for this incredible paradox.

102
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:56,120
Put yourself for a moment in the shoes of citizens or businesses.

103
00:06:56,120 --> 00:07:00,039
If you know for sure that taxes will go down in a year, what do you do?

104
00:07:00,080 --> 00:07:02,319
Simple: you put everything on hold.

105
00:07:02,319 --> 00:07:04,879
Why spend or invest huge amounts of capital today?

106
00:07:04,879 --> 00:07:08,439
If tomorrow, thanks to the tax cut, it will cost you much less?

107
00:07:08,439 --> 00:07:12,560
This mass behavior generates the initial contraction of the economy.

108
00:07:12,560 --> 00:07:15,000
Everyone delays important decisions.

109
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,680
And the biggest irony that researchers discovered is that the longer this wait is,

110
00:07:19,680 --> 00:07:24,720
the weaker the subsequent economic expansion will be when the cut finally takes effect.

111
00:07:24,720 --> 00:07:28,600
And all this leaves us with a truly powerful final provocation,

112
00:07:28,600 --> 00:07:30,320
worth reflecting on.

113
00:07:30,320 --> 00:07:36,000
Having extreme political transparency and knowing the future in advance thanks to these public speeches

114
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:39,080
ends up damaging our economy in the present;

115
00:07:39,080 --> 00:07:42,360
it's a fascinating thought that overturns quite a few beliefs

116
00:07:42,360 --> 00:07:46,760
we have about how politicians communicate and how efficient markets are.

117
00:07:46,760 --> 00:07:50,840
In short, today we clearly saw that words are never just words.

118
00:07:50,840 --> 00:07:54,680
They can be measured, they turn into data, they move capital,

119
00:07:54,680 --> 00:07:58,080
and sometimes they create true unexpected paradoxes.

120
00:07:58,079 --> 00:08:01,199
Our analysis ends here, but one thing is certain.

121
00:08:01,199 --> 00:08:04,839
The next time you hear a politician talking about taxes on TV,

122
00:08:04,839 --> 00:08:09,039
those words will have a significantly different weight and meaning.